I made these super easy clouds for the window at @charliepickles_ and in hindsight, I should have documented it by video but I was cranky and was sure it wasn’t going to work out. But…it did. So… ta-da! These would be SO cute in a playroom or nursery! 

All you need is chicken wire and batting and some clear string / fishing line.

1. I crushed chicken wire loosely into a ball and then stuffed the batting inside and started pulling it outwards. No glue required. 

2. I hung fishing line from left and right to form a triangle which kept the cloud level. 

3. I attached it from 1 longer string to the ceiling. You can see this in the pictures if you look closely. 

I’d be happy to do a video but the beauty of this project is that clouds are NOT perfect. So this project is perfect even for grumpy days when your confidence in yourself is low. 🤣
Never leaving. 📍Stocking Island, Bahamas

I can’t really explain the feeling of this trip, except I’ve said “I can’t believe this” about a thousand  times. 

The Exumas have been a bucket list trip for me for a decade or more and I put off thinking about it leading up to it for fear that something would derail it - delayed or cancelled flights, lost luggage - something. So when we actually got here - no hiccups at all, I felt pretty emotional. There is something here that is extraordinary - the people of the island are amazing, the other travellers feel like minded in appreciating and respecting nature. Today we took a taxi to Hoopers Bay where we walked down rickety steps to get to the beach and found sea turtles in their natural habitat. And we got to swim with them - and admire their beauty from up close. 🐢🌊🌴

Hopped on the water taxi from our hotel to Stocking Island (the other side of our hotel) to trek around the waters edge to find and eat at the famous @chatnchill, the land of the conchs and stingrays. 🙌🏻🫶🏻🌊🌴
Rolling mossy hills, palms and brick estates overlooking turquoise waters. Heaven.
Bucket list ✔️Got to swim with the 🐷🌴🌊
Felt like I was in a 🦖🦕 movie - Rock Iguanas. Super friendly - especially if you have grapes. 🍇

We fell in love with Exuma. And I’m already figuring out how fast we can get back. Thank you to the people who welcomed us in Exuma, the most kind and welcoming people. @driftwoodexuma @peacenplentyresort @chatnchill @exumawatersports and to @dinutv for all the tips on where to go. 🙌🏻

Chicago Summed up in some pictures! ⁠
⁠
First - The architecture in Chicago is amazing. Everyone told me about it, but when you get there you really see how crazy amazing it is.⁠
⁠
Here are some things we did:⁠
⁠
1. We took the architectural river tour that everyone recommended (and rightfully so). We went on a dusk boat tour which was truly special. ⁠
⁠
2. We Tried Deep Dish Pizza (Order a smaller pie than you think.) ⁠
⁠
3. Took a walk along the River Walk and loved seeing the city that way ⁠
⁠
4. Went to the top of @willistowerchicago - It was fun to see a history of Chicago and the building as a lead up to the super cramped (but super fast) elevator ride to the top. ⁠
⁠
5. The Shedd Aquarium (@shedd_aquarium) was a must⁠
⁠
6. Museum of Science and Industry (@MSIchicago) was one of our favourite places and we stayed most of the day ⁠
⁠
7. I fell in love with @colorfactoryco in NYC and wanted to visit the Chicago version. Sadly the Chicago version wasn't as dynamite as NYC but we had fun none the less!

There you go. No more Chicago spam. 🤪

Hi friends. I’ve written this post a dozen times since September but haven’t been able to finish it. Truthfully I don’t really even want write this post, but I’m hoping it may help my healing process. It’s also World Mental Health Day which seems fitting to be the day I post. 

In September, I took Jake, our beloved little Chihuahua for a walk at the cottage, when Jake was violently attacked by an off leash dog. In trying to save Jake I was also hurt. Jake didn’t survive the attack.

Aubrey did his best to reach out to our friends and family to let them know about the attack in the days after, but it became too hard to try to tell everyone. It’s even hard to even compose this. We’re processing lots of feelings. 

I’m surrounded by the most supportive people - like my husband, my family and friends.

I’m seeking counselling to deal with the attack and have found it helpful. I’m working through PTSD and guilt, and sadness.

Anyhow, all of this to explain why I have a scar on my face, why we’re not walking Jake, he’s not at the shop, and with us at school pickups. 

We miss him terribly. 

Xo Lindsay
